{{Quote|This place is the Holy Grail for them. And, you know, we actually have a few Holy Grails here.|Noah Skinner (a member of the Skywalker Ranch Fire Brigade) on fans' fascination with the ranch|<ref name="Ranch">{{WebCite|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-tm-skywalker-03march2.pg-photogallery.html|text=The Secrets of Skywalker|author=Geoff Boucher & Gregg Segal|work=[[Wikipedia:Los Angeles Times|''Los Angeles Times'']]|archivedate=20150120014016}}</ref>}}
[[File:SkywalkerRanch-TCSBRBD1.png|thumb|right|300px|An aerial view of the ranch]]
'''Skywalker Ranch''' is the name of the workplace of [[Wikipedia:Film director|film director]] and [[Wikipedia:Film producer|producer]] [[George Lucas]] in secluded but open country near [[Wikipedia:Nicasio, California|Nicasio, California]] in [[Wikipedia:Marin County, California|Marin County]]. The ranch is located on [[Wikipedia:Lucas Valley-Marinwood, California|Lucas Valley]] Road, although Lucas is not related to the road's namesake, a turn-of-the-century landowner in the area. The Ranch is not open to the public and keeps a low profile from the road.<ref name="star-tribune">{{WebCite|url=http://www.startribune.com/389/story/26653.html|text=Skywalker Ranch: George Lucas creates a magic world in real life|author=Jeff Strickler|date=2002-05-18|work=[[Wikipedia:Star Tribune|''Star Tribune'']]|archivedate=20071010052547}}</ref>

Before the [[1800s]], the land that would one day house Skywalker Ranch was home to the [[Wikipedia:Coast Miwok|Coast Miwok Tribe]]. The fact that "Miwok" rhymes with "[[Ewok]]" has led to speculation on whether the Ewoks&mdash;being an isolated civilization that was under threat by a colonial power, in their case the [[Galactic Empire]]&mdash;were inspired by the struggles of indigenous peoples.<ref name="Stewards of the Forest Moon">{{InsiderCite|212|Stewards of the Forest Moon}}</ref> [[George Lucas]] has confirmed the connection was intentional.<ref name="Where There's Life">{{BookCite|author=Jeffrey Miller|title=Where There's Life, There's Lawsuits: Not Altogether Serious Ruminations on Law and Life|publisher=ECW Press|date=2003|language=English|isbn=1550225014|quote=I took the end of Wookiee, the 'ie' of Wookiee, and put it at the head, like Pig Latin, and then started, when I said it phonetically, it sounded like Ewok which is very similar to Miwok which is the Indians that sort of inhabited the area where I live and where my studio is. Matter of fact, there was a Miwok village just outside my office. So I thought that was a nice, nice sort of reverberation of the idea and eventually took the 'i' and one of the 'os' out and it was Ewok.|link=http://books.google.com/books?id=BkcMEKm_XUYC&pg=PA146&lpg=PA146&dq=ewok+miwok&source=bl&ots=0mkV5S1x6C&sig=PkujK-xc9pZdRYpNn0h_MJ_kMuc&hl=en&ei=6q-wSa_AL9CCtwet0qDDBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result#PPA146,M1}}</ref> Miwok tribe member Lucina Thomas-Vidauri spoke fondly of this possible connection to ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'', saying that she hopes ''[[Star Wars]]'' fans will learn more about her culture thanks to the connection.<ref name="Stewards of the Forest Moon" /> Assembled parcel by parcel since [[September]] [[1978]],<ref name="Timeline">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/article/2005/05/13/online-only-expanded-timeline-star-wars-history|text='Star Wars' Timeline|author=Jeff Labrecque|date=2005-05-10|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20190806114542}}</ref> Skywalker Ranch has cost Lucas up to US$100 million, according to the [[Wikipedia:Wall Street Journal|''Wall Street Journal'']]. After neighboring ranchers complained that Skywalker Ranch was polluting the environment, Lucasfilm acquired 3,000 acres (12 km²) of adjoining land for a total of over 4,700 acres (19 km²). Only 15 acres (60,000 m²) have been developed.<ref name="Build">{{WebCite|url=http://www.marinij.com/westmarin/ci_5564105|text=Lucas can build additions, bridge on Skywalker ranch|date=2007-03-31|work=[[Wikipedia:Marin Independent Journal|''Marin Independent Journal'']]|archivedate=20070929091445|nolive=1}}</ref>

[[File:SkywalkerRanchMainHouse.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The main house at Skywalker Ranch]]
The Ranch contains a barn with animals, vineyards, a garden with fruits and vegetables used in the on-site restaurant, an outdoor swimming pool and fitness center with [[Wikipedia:Racquetball|racquetball]] courts, the man-made "Lake Ewok", a hilltop observatory, a 300-seat theater called "The Stag" as well as multiple theater screening rooms, and parking that is mostly concealed underground to preserve the natural landscape.<ref name="seattle-pi">{{WebCite|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Inside-the-secure-world-of-Skywalker-Ranch-1173112.php|text=Inside the secure world of Skywalker Ranch|author=William Arnold|date=2005-05-12|work=[[Wikipedia:Seattle Post-Intelligencer|''Seattle Post-Intelligencer'']]|archivedate=20121015222946}}</ref> [[Skywalker Sound]] was moved onto the ranch in [[1987]], now occupying the Technical Building.<ref name="Skysound">{{SkySound|url=about|text=History|archivedate=20190114153631}}</ref> The Main House has a company research library under a stained-glass dome.<ref name="star-tribune" /> Skywalker Ranch has its own fire station, which is part of the Marin County Mutual Aid system, and is often called on to assist firefighters in nearby Marinwood.<ref name="star-tribune" /> Lucas also created a fictional backstory for the ranch, in which it "was once owned by an old sea captain".<ref>{{WebCite|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/21/movies/meanwhile-back-at-the-ranch.html|text=Meanwhile, Back at the Ranch|author=Richard B. Woodward|date=1989-05-21|work=[[Wikipedia:The New York Times|''The New York Times'']]|archivedate=20150403061341}}</ref> In [[2007]], Marin County gave Lucas permission to add two more screening rooms and a bridge across Bull Tail Creek.<ref name="Build" />

The Main House has a safe where legal tablets with Lucas's ''Star Wars'' notes are kept. Under its foundation is a time capsule (buried in [[1981]]) that contains Lucas's attorney's letter confirming the agreement with 20th Century-Fox. A barn next to a horse corral houses props, scale models, costumes and artwork from the ''Star Wars'' movies, including lightsaber hilts, Luke's landspeeder and the carbonite slab. Another building houses storyboards, concept art and other illustrations.<ref>''[[The Secrets of Star Wars: Shadows of the Empire]]''</ref>

Lucas, who based his ''Star Wars'' films on the scholarship of [[Wikipedia:Joseph Campbell|Joseph Campbell]], was involved in the creation of the [[1988]] documentary which explored Campbell's works of [[Wikipedia:The Power of Myth|''The Power of Myth'']]. The series of six, one-hour interviews between Campbell and journalist [[Wikipedia:Bill Moyers|Bill Moyers]] was filmed at Skywalker Ranch.<ref name="Master Mythologist">{{WebCite|url=http://www.pacifica.edu/campbell/campbell04_news.html|text=Remembering a Master Mythologist and His Connection to Santa Barbara|author=Tom Jacobs|date=2004-03-24|work=[[Wikipedia:Santa Barbara News-Press|''Santa Barbara News-Press'']]|archivedate=20040617080944}}.</ref> In the first episode, Moyers discusses Campbell's friendship with Lucas and the impact of his scholarship on Lucas' ''Star Wars'' films (Episodes IV, V, and VI).<ref name="TV.com">{{TVcom|url=shows/joseph-campbell-and-the-power-of-myth/the-heros-adventure-432756|text=The Hero's Adventure}}</ref>

Skywalker Ranch is intended to be more of a "filmmaker's retreat" than a headquarters for Lucas's business operations. The headquarters of [[Lucasfilm]], [[Industrial Light & Magic]], and [[LucasArts]] are located in Lucas's [[Letterman Digital Arts Center]] in the [[Wikipedia:Presidio of San Francisco#Letterman Digital Arts Center and Lucasfilm|Presidio of San Francisco]].<ref name="seattle-pi" /> Lucas does not live on the Ranch.<ref name="star-tribune" />

After the release of the [[2005]] film [[Star Wars: Episode III Revenge of the Sith|''Revenge of the Sith'']], [[Hayden Christensen]], the actor who played [[Anakin Skywalker]] in the [[prequel trilogy]], made visits to the Ranch and was motivated by the "sense of peace and escape" he felt. He then took a break from [[Wikipedia:Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] in general and bought a [[farm]] in the [[Wikipedia:Canada|Canadian]] countryside.<ref name="17 year">{{WebCite|url=https://ew.com/tv/obi-wan-kenobi-ewan-mcgregor-hayden-christensen-cover-story|text=Inside the 17-year journey to reunite Ewan McGregor and Hayden Christensen for ''Obi-Wan Kenobi''|author=Dalton Ross|date=2022-03-10|work=''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''|archivedate=20220310151626}}</ref>

==Big Rock Ranch==
Big Rock Ranch is a later Lucasfilm development in Marin county on Lucas Valley Road adjacent to Skywalker Ranch. The county's planning commission approved this facility in September [[1996]]<ref name="Permit">{{WebCite|url=http://www.co.marin.ca.us/depts/CD/main/mcbds/plng/devproj/lucsr-1.html|text=Lucasfilm, Ltd. Master Plan and Use Permit with construction|author=[[Lucasfilm Ltd.|Lucasfilm, Ltd.]]|date=1996-09-25|work=[[Wikipedia:Marin County, California|County of Marin]]|archivedate=20030704111035|nolive=1}}</ref> and construction was completed in August 2002.<ref name="CMA">{{WebCite|url=http://www.cmaincsf.com/services/bigrockranch1.html|text=Big Rock Ranch Project|work=[http://www.cmaincsf.com CMA]|archivedate=20021015115329|nolive=1}}</ref> However in November [[2004]], Lucas announced that the 250 employees of the ranch were to be moved to the Letterman Digital Arts Center.<ref name="Kravets 2004">{{WebCite|url=http://www.ptreyeslight.com/stories/nov25_04/lucasfilm_move.html|text=Lucasfilm to transfer much of its workforce|author=Jim Kravets|date=2004-11-24|work=[[Wikipedia:Point Reyes Light (newspaper)|''Point Reyes Light'']]|archivedate=20041128055536|nolive=1}}</ref>

The ranch comprises 1061 acres (4.3 km²), of which 43 acres (17 hectares) are developed with 317,000 ft² (29,500 m²) of office space.<ref name="CMA" /> Before the Presidio move in 2005, Big Rock Ranch housed the marketing, licensing, distribution and online divisions of Lucasfilm.<ref name="Kravets 2004" /> It is currently the headquarters of the animation division as of 2007.<ref name="Vilmur 2007">{{SWArchive|url=theclonewars/blogs/f20070921/index.html|text=Clone Wars at the Ranch}}</ref>

